[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] An approximation Q to the integral of $f(x)$ over the interval $[a,b]$ is computed (line 2), as well as an error estimate $\varepsilon$ (line 3).
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] If the estimated error is larger than the required tolerance $\tau$ (line 4), the interval is subdivided (line 5) and the quadrature is applied on both halves separately (line 6).
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Either the initial estimate or the sum of the recursively computed halves is returned (line 7).
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] and the logic for deciding which interval to subdivide, and when to terminate.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] There are several variants of this scheme.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] The most common will be discussed later.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] where the nodes $x_{i}$ and weights $w_{i}$ are generally precomputed.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Other quadrature rules, such as Gaussian quadrature or Gauss-Kronrod quadrature, may also be used.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] An algorithm may elect to use different quadrature methods on different subintervals, for example using a high-order method only where the integrand is smooth.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Some quadrature algorithms generate a sequence of results which should approach the correct value.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Otherwise one can use a "null rule" which has the form of the above quadrature rule, but whose value would be zero for a simple integrand (for example, if the integrand were a polynomial of the appropriate degree).
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] "Local" adaptive quadrature makes the acceptable error for a given interval proportional to the length of that interval.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] This criterion can be difficult to satisfy if the integrands are badly behaved at only a few points, for example with a few step discontinuities.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Alternatively, one could require only that the sum of the errors on each of the subintervals be less than the user's requirement.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] This would be "global" adaptive quadrature.
[src:numerical-quadrature/adaptive-quadrature] Global adaptive quadrature can be more efficient (using fewer evaluations of the integrand) but is generally more complex to program and may require more working space to record information on the current set of intervals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] In numerical analysis, the **Newton–Cotes formulas**, also called the **Newton–Cotes quadrature rules** or simply **Newton–Cotes rules**, are a group of formulas for numerical integration (also called *quadrature*) based on evaluating the integrand at equally spaced points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] They are named after Isaac Newton, who originated the formulas, and Roger Cotes, who expanded upon Newton's work.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Newton–Cotes formulas can be useful if the value of the integrand at equally spaced points is given and when the integrand is known to have only a finite number of continuous derivatives.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] If the integrand is infinitely differentiable and it is possible to change the points at which the integrand is evaluated, then other methods such as Gaussian quadrature and Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature may yield higher precision per function evaluation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] It is assumed that the value of a function f defined on $[a,b]$ is known at $n+1$ equally spaced points: $a\leq x_{0}<x_{1}<\dots <x_{n}\leq b$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] There are two classes of Newton–Cotes quadrature: they are called "closed" when $x_{0}=a$ and $x_{n}=b$ , i.e. they use the function values at the interval endpoints, and "open" when $x_{0}>a$ and $x_{n}<b$ , i.e. they do not use the function values at the endpoints.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The number h is called *step size*, $w_{i}$ are called *weights*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The weights can be computed as the integral of Lagrange basis polynomials.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] They depend only on $x_{i}$ and not on the function f.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] A Newton–Cotes formula of any degree n can be constructed.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] However, for large n a Newton–Cotes rule can sometimes suffer from catastrophic Runge's phenomenon where the error grows exponentially for large n.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Methods such as Gaussian quadrature and Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature with unequally spaced points (clustered at the *endpoints* of the integration interval) are stable and much more accurate, and are normally preferred to Newton–Cotes.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] If these methods cannot be used, because the integrand is only given at the fixed equidistributed grid, then Runge's phenomenon can be avoided by using a composite rule, as explained below.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Alternatively, stable Newton–Cotes formulas can be constructed using least-squares approximation instead of interpolation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] This allows building numerically stable formulas even for high degrees.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] This table lists some of the Newton–Cotes formulas of the closed type.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Newton-Cotes rules using more points may involve negatively weighted nodes.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Higher order methods are generally viewed as suffering from to Runge's phenomena (see above).
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] Boole's rule is sometimes mistakenly called Bode's rule, as a result of the propagation of a typographical error in Abramowitz and Stegun, an early reference book.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The exponent of the step size *h* in the error term gives the rate at which the approximation error decreases.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The order of the derivative of *f* in the error term gives the lowest degree of a polynomial which can no longer be integrated exactly (i.e. with error equal to zero) with this rule.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The number $\xi$ must be taken from the interval (*a*,*b*), therefore, the error bound is equal to the error term when $f(\xi )=\max(f(x)),a<x<b$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] This table lists some of the Newton–Cotes formulas of the open type.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] The formulas approximate the integral over the interval $(a,b)$ without having to evaluate the integrand at either endpoint.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] This is useful in cases where the end-point is known to be a singularity.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] However, in cases of 2 or more points, these rules do not compound as nicely as the standard closed-interval rules; a gap of $2h$ is left between samples of adjoining panels.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] For the Newton–Cotes rules to be accurate, the step size h needs to be small, which means that the interval of integration $[a,b]$ must be small itself, which is not true most of the time.
[src:numerical-quadrature/newton-cotes-formulas] For this reason, one usually performs numerical integration by splitting $[a,b]$ into smaller subintervals, applying a Newton–Cotes rule on each subinterval, and adding up the results.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] In analysis, **numerical integration** comprises a broad family of algorithms for calculating the numerical value of a definite integral.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The term **numerical quadrature** (often abbreviated to **quadrature**) is more or less a synonym for "numerical integration", especially as applied to one-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Some authors refer to numerical integration over more than one dimension as **cubature**; others take "quadrature" to include higher-dimensional integration.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] If *f*(*x*) is a smooth function integrated over a small number of dimensions, and the domain of integration is bounded, there are many methods for approximating the integral to the desired precision.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Numerical integration has roots in the geometrical problem of finding a square with the same area as a given plane figure (*quadrature* or *squaring*), as in the quadrature of the circle.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The term is also sometimes used to describe the numerical solution of differential equations.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A formula for the integrand may be known, but it may be difficult or impossible to find an antiderivative that is an elementary function.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] An example of such an integrand is *f* (*x*) = exp(−*x*2), the antiderivative of which (the error function, times a constant) cannot be written in elementary form .
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] It may be possible to find an antiderivative symbolically, but it may be easier to compute a numerical approximation than to compute the antiderivative.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] That may be the case if the antiderivative is given as an infinite series or product, or if its evaluation requires a special function that is not available.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The term "numerical integration" first appears in 1915 in the publication *A Course in Interpolation and Numeric Integration for the Mathematical Laboratory* by David Gibb.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] "Quadrature" is a historical mathematical term that means calculating area.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Quadrature problems have served as one of the main sources of mathematical analysis.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Mathematicians of Ancient Greece, according to the Pythagorean doctrine, understood calculation of area as the process of constructing geometrically a square having the same area (*squaring*) — that is why the process was named "quadrature".
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Examples include quadrature of the circle, Lune of Hippocrates, and the treatise *Quadrature of the Parabola*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This construction must be performed only by means of compass and straightedge.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The ancient Babylonians used the trapezoidal rule to integrate the motion of Jupiter along the ecliptic.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] For a quadrature of a rectangle with the sides *a* and *b* it is necessary to construct a square with the side $x={\sqrt {ab}}$ (the geometric mean of *a* and *b*).
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] For this purpose it is possible to use the following fact: if we draw the circle with the sum of *a* and *b* as the diameter, then the height BH (from a point of their connection to crossing with a circle) equals their geometric mean.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The similar geometrical construction solves a problem of a quadrature for a parallelogram and a triangle.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Problems of quadrature for curvilinear figures are much more difficult.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the circle with compass and straightedge had been proved in the 19th century to be impossible.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Nevertheless, for some figures (for example the lune of Hippocrates) a quadrature can be performed.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The quadratures of a sphere surface and a parabola segment done by Archimedes became the highest achievement of the antique analysis.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] To prove the results, Archimedes used the method of exhaustion of Eudoxus.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] In medieval Europe the quadrature meant calculation of area by any method.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] More often the method of indivisibles was used; it was less rigorous, but more simple and powerful.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] John Wallis algebrised this method: he wrote in his *Arithmetica Infinitorum* (1656) series that we now call the definite integral, and he calculated their values.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Isaac Barrow and James Gregory made further progress: quadratures for some algebraic curves and spirals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Christiaan Huygens successfully performed a quadrature of some solids of revolution.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The quadrature of the hyperbola by Saint-Vincent and de Sarasa provided a new function, the natural logarithm, of critical importance.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] With the invention of integral calculus came a universal method for area calculation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] In response, the term "quadrature" has become traditional, and instead the modern phrase "*computation of a univariate definite integral*" is more common.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A **quadrature rule** is an approximation of the definite integral of a function, usually stated as a weighted sum of function values at specified points within the domain of integration.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Numerical integration methods can generally be described as combining evaluations of the integrand to get an approximation to the integral.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The integrand is evaluated at a finite set of points called ***integration points*** and a weighted sum of these values is used to approximate the integral.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The integration points and weights depend on the specific method used and the accuracy required from the approximation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] An important part of the analysis of any numerical integration method is to study the behavior of the approximation error as a function of the number of integrand evaluations.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A method that yields a small error for a small number of evaluations is usually considered superior.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Reducing the number of evaluations of the integrand reduces the number of arithmetic operations involved, and therefore reduces the total error.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Also, each evaluation takes time, and the integrand may be arbitrarily complicated.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A "brute force" kind of numerical integration can be done, if the integrand is reasonably well-behaved (i.e. piecewise continuous and of bounded variation), by evaluating the integrand with very small increments.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This simplest method approximates the function by a step function (a piecewise constant function, or a segmented polynomial of degree zero) that passes through the point ${\textstyle \left({\frac {a+b}{2}},f\left({\frac {a+b}{2}}\right)\right)}$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A large class of quadrature rules can be derived by constructing interpolating functions that are easy to integrate.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Typically these interpolating functions are polynomials.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] In practice, since polynomials of very high degree tend to oscillate wildly, only polynomials of low degree are used, typically linear and quadratic.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The interpolating function may be a straight line (an affine function, i.e. a polynomial of degree 1) passing through the points $\left(a,f(a)\right)$ and $\left(b,f(b)\right)$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] For either one of these rules, we can make a more accurate approximation by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into some number n of subintervals, computing an approximation for each subinterval, then adding up all the results.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This is called a *composite rule*, *extended rule*, or *iterated rule*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] where the subintervals have the form $[a+kh,a+(k+1)h]\subset [a,b],$ with ${\textstyle h={\frac {b-a}{n}}}$ and $k=0,\ldots ,n-1.$ Here we used subintervals of the same length h but one could also use intervals of varying length $\left(h_{k}\right)_{k}$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Interpolation with polynomials evaluated at equally spaced points in $[a,b]$ yields the Newton–Cotes formulas, of which the rectangle rule and the trapezoidal rule are examples.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Simpson's rule, which is based on a polynomial of order 2, is also a Newton–Cotes formula.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Quadrature rules with equally spaced points have the very convenient property of *nesting*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The corresponding rule with each interval subdivided includes all the current points, so those integrand values can be re-used.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] If we allow the intervals between interpolation points to vary, we find another group of quadrature formulas, such as the Gaussian quadrature formulas.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A Gaussian quadrature rule is typically more accurate than a Newton–Cotes rule that uses the same number of function evaluations, if the integrand is smooth (i.e., if it is sufficiently differentiable).
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Other quadrature methods with varying intervals include Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature (also called Fejér quadrature) methods, which do nest.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Gaussian quadrature rules do not nest, but the related Gauss–Kronrod quadrature formulas do.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Adaptive quadrature is a numerical integration method in which the integral of a function $f(x)$ is approximated using static quadrature rules on adaptively refined subintervals of the region of integration.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Generally, adaptive algorithms are just as efficient and effective as traditional algorithms for "well behaved" integrands, but are also effective for "badly behaved" integrands for which traditional algorithms may fail.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The accuracy of a quadrature rule of the Newton–Cotes type is generally a function of the number of evaluation points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The result is usually more accurate as the number of evaluation points increases, or, equivalently, as the width of the step size between the points decreases.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] It is natural to ask what the result would be if the step size were allowed to approach zero.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This can be answered by extrapolating the result from two or more nonzero step sizes, using series acceleration methods such as Richardson extrapolation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The extrapolation function may be a polynomial or rational function.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Extrapolation methods are described in more detail by Stoer and Bulirsch (Section 3.4) and are implemented in many of the routines in the QUADPACK library.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] where the supremum was used to approximate.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Hence, if we approximate the integral ${\textstyle \int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx}$ by the quadrature rule $(b-a)f(a)$ our error is no greater than the right hand side of **1**.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] We can convert this into an error analysis for the Riemann sum, giving an upper bound of ${\frac {n^{-1}}{2}}\sup _{0\leq x\leq 1}\left|f'(x)\right|$ for the error term of that particular approximation.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] (Note that this is precisely the error we calculated for the example $f(x)=x$ .) Using more derivatives, and by tweaking the quadrature, we can do a similar error analysis using a Taylor series (using a partial sum with remainder term) for *f*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This error analysis gives a strict upper bound on the error, if the derivatives of *f* are available.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This integration method can be combined with interval arithmetic to produce computer proofs and *verified* calculations.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Several methods exist for approximate integration over unbounded intervals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The standard technique involves specially derived quadrature rules, such as Gauss-Hermite quadrature for integrals on the whole real line and Gauss-Laguerre quadrature for integrals on the positive reals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The quadrature rules discussed so far are all designed to compute one-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] To compute integrals in multiple dimensions, one approach is to phrase the multiple integral as repeated one-dimensional integrals by applying Fubini's theorem (the tensor product rule).
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This approach requires the function evaluations to grow exponentially as the number of dimensions increases.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Three methods are known to overcome this so-called *curse of dimensionality*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A great many additional techniques for forming multidimensional cubature integration rules for a variety of weighting functions are given in the monograph by Stroud.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Integration on the sphere has been reviewed by Hesse et al.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Monte Carlo methods and quasi-Monte Carlo methods are easy to apply to multi-dimensional integrals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] They may yield greater accuracy for the same number of function evaluations than repeated integrations using one-dimensional methods.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] A large class of useful Monte Carlo methods are the so-called Markov chain Monte Carlo algorithms, which include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm and Gibbs sampling.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Sparse grids were originally developed by Smolyak for the quadrature of high-dimensional functions.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The method is always based on a one-dimensional quadrature rule, but performs a more sophisticated combination of univariate results.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] However, whereas the tensor product rule guarantees that the weights of all of the cubature points will be positive if the weights of the quadrature points were positive, Smolyak's rule does not guarantee that the weights will all be positive.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Bayesian quadrature is a statistical approach to the numerical problem of computing integrals and falls under the field of probabilistic numerics.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] It can provide a full handling of the uncertainty over the solution of the integral expressed as a Gaussian process posterior variance.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] can be reduced to an initial value problem for an ordinary differential equation by applying the first part of the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Numerical methods for ordinary differential equations, such as Runge–Kutta methods, can be applied to the restated problem and thus be used to evaluate the integral.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] For instance, the standard fourth-order Runge–Kutta method applied to the differential equation yields Simpson's rule from above.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The differential equation $F'(x)=f(x)$ has a special form: the right-hand side contains only the independent variable (here x ) and not the dependent variable (here F ).
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] This simplifies the theory and algorithms considerably.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] The problem of evaluating integrals is thus best studied in its own right.
[src:numerical-quadrature/numerical-integration] Conversely, the term "quadrature" may also be used for the solution of differential equations: "solving by quadrature" or "reduction to quadrature" means expressing its solution in terms of integrals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] In numerical analysis, **Romberg's method** is used to estimate the definite integral $\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx$ by applying Richardson extrapolation repeatedly on the trapezium rule or the rectangle rule (midpoint rule).
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The estimates generate a triangular array.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] Romberg's method is a Newton–Cotes formula – it evaluates the integrand at equally spaced points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The integrand must have continuous derivatives, though fairly good results may be obtained if only a few derivatives exist.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] If it is possible to evaluate the integrand at unequally spaced points, then other methods such as Gaussian quadrature and Clenshaw–Curtis quadrature are generally more accurate.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The method is named after Werner Romberg, who published the method in 1955.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The zeroth extrapolation, *R*(*n*, 0), is equivalent to the trapezoidal rule with 2*n* + 1 points; the first extrapolation, *R*(*n*, 1), is equivalent to Simpson's rule with 2*n* + 1 points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The second extrapolation, *R*(*n*, 2), is equivalent to Boole's rule with 2*n* + 1 points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The further extrapolations differ from Newton-Cotes formulas.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] In particular further Romberg extrapolations expand on Boole's rule in very slight ways, modifying weights into ratios similar as in Boole's rule.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] In contrast, further Newton-Cotes methods produce increasingly differing weights, eventually leading to large positive and negative weights.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] This is indicative of how large degree interpolating polynomial Newton-Cotes methods fail to converge for many integrals, while Romberg integration is more stable.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] When function evaluations are expensive, it may be preferable to replace the polynomial interpolation of Richardson with the rational interpolation proposed by Bulirsch & Stoer (1967).
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] To estimate the area under a curve the trapezoid rule is applied first to one-piece, then two, then four, and so on.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] After trapezoid rule estimates are obtained, Richardson extrapolation is applied.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] As an example, the Gaussian function is integrated from 0 to 1, i.e. the error function erf(1) ≈ 0.842700792949715.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The triangular array is calculated row by row and calculation is terminated if the two last entries in the last row differ less than 10−8.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] The result in the lower right corner of the triangular array is accurate to the digits shown.
[src:numerical-quadrature/romberg-s-method] It is remarkable that this result is derived from the less accurate approximations obtained by the trapezium rule in the first column of the triangular array.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] In numerical integration, **Simpson's rules** are several approximations for definite integrals, named after Thomas Simpson (1710–1761).
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] In German and some other languages, it is named after Johannes Kepler, who derived it in 1615 after seeing it used for wine barrels (barrel rule, *Keplersche Fassregel*).
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] The approximate equality in the rule becomes exact if *f* is a polynomial up to and including 3rd degree.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] If the 1/3 rule is applied to *n* equal subdivisions of the integration range [*a*, *b*], one obtains the **composite Simpson's 1/3 rule**.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Points inside the integration range are given alternating weights 4/3 and 2/3.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] If the 3/8 rule is applied to *n* equal subdivisions of the integration range [*a*, *b*], one obtains the **composite Simpson's 3/8 rule**.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Simpson's 1/3 and 3/8 rules are two special cases of closed Newton–Cotes formulas.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] In naval architecture and ship stability estimation, there also exists *Simpson's third rule*, which has no special importance in general numerical analysis, see Simpson's rules (ship stability).
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Simpson's 1/3 rule, also simply called Simpson's rule, is a method for numerical integration proposed by Thomas Simpson.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] It is based upon a quadratic interpolation and is the **composite Simpson's 1/3 rule** evaluated for $n=2$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] The error is asymptotically proportional to $(b-a)^{5}$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] However, the above derivations suggest an error proportional to $(b-a)^{4}$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Simpson's rule gains an extra order because the points at which the integrand is evaluated are distributed symmetrically in the interval $[a,\ b]$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Since the error term is proportional to the fourth derivative of f at $\xi$ , this shows that Simpson's rule provides exact results for any polynomial f of degree three or less, since the fourth derivative of such a polynomial is zero at all points.
