[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Using another approximation (for example, the trapezoidal rule with twice as many points), it is possible to take a suitable weighted average and eliminate another error term.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] The coefficients α, β and γ can be fixed by requiring that this approximation be exact for all quadratic polynomials.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] If the interval of integration $[a,b]$ is in some sense "small", then Simpson's rule with $n=2$ subintervals will provide an adequate approximation to the exact integral.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] By "small" we mean that the function being integrated is relatively smooth over the interval $[a,b]$ .
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] For such a function, a smooth quadratic interpolant like the one used in Simpson's rule will give good results.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] However, it is often the case that the function we are trying to integrate is not smooth over the interval.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Typically, this means that either the function is highly oscillatory or lacks derivatives at certain points.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] In these cases, Simpson's rule may give very poor results.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] One common way of handling this problem is by breaking up the interval $[a,b]$ into $n>2$ small subintervals.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Simpson's rule is then applied to each subinterval, with the results being summed to produce an approximation for the integral over the entire interval.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] This sort of approach is termed the *composite Simpson's 1/3 rule*, or just *composite Simpson's rule*.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] Suppose that the interval $[a,b]$ is split up into n subintervals, with n an even number.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] The error committed by the composite Simpson's rule is $-{\frac {1}{180}}h^{4}(b-a)f^{(4)}(\xi ),$ where $\xi$ is some number between a and b , and $h=(b-a)/n$ is the "step length".
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] This formulation splits the interval $[a,b]$ in subintervals of equal length.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] In practice, it is often advantageous to use subintervals of different lengths and concentrate the efforts on the places where the integrand is less well-behaved.
[src:numerical-quadrature/simpson-s-rule] This leads to the adaptive Simpson's method.
